Bypassing the fact that this is the latest entry in the ever-growing  genre (which isn't really affecting my vote but not really exciting me all that much either), as a story this was somewhat predictable in terms of what happens to the D-Class. That on its own also doesn't really affect my vote either, but as a narrative it's not offering a whole lot to add to the initial concept.

Speaking of that, the initial concept isn't a bad one. There's a certain mystery as to why there are all these chairs in separate little units, which get more and more demonstrative of the whole  thing you're going for here. Where my downvote got sealed was the way in which the mystery is revealed, which was both way too literal for my tastes in terms of what's doing this and sort of a direct, mundane explanation for something so weird. I also didn't care much for the fact that you've got two D-Class expositing for us who both happen to enjoy pontificating despite the dangerous and unearthly situation that they're in.







